			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Conservatism and Liberalism...<a name="43836"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jun 2 04 9:21 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">
<br />
But instead someone who realizes that issues are not black and white and therefore want to get to know the whole issue as best they can to make a good decision.
<br />
</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
I agree... what's wrong with our country is that not enough people do this.
<br />
How many people read both sides of an issue before taking a stand? Besides paying attention to mainstream media (which is fairly close to neutral on most issues despite the whining of certain partisan pundits) most people only read/watch the media that's biased in their favor. How many left-wingers listen to Rush Limbaugh, Sean Hannity, or read Ann Coulter, or watch Bill O'Reilly? By the same token, how many right-wingers read Mother Jones or the Utne Reader? And of those who do, how many are actually interested in what the opposing side have to say and aren't just trolling for something to make themselves mad?
<br />

<br />
Especially when it comes to foreign affairs. Prior to 9-11, if you compared the amount of time given to foreign issues on TV to, say, the proportion of news stories on foreign issues in Reuters (which is a British company, BTW), or on PBS, you'll find that commercial American news media tended to devote disproportionately less time to foreign policy matters. Why? Because it's complicated and boring and often depressing and doesn't really get ratings.
<br />

<br />
So, 9-11 occurred, and the vast majority of Americans didn't understand why it happened, didn't understand our relationships with these countries that generated the terrorists, and didn't understand the complex interrelations between the various countries of the middle east. A tiny tiny minority of Americans would be able to take a map of the middle east and point out which countries (other than Iraq and Afganistan) are our enemies, which are our friends, and which are in between. And yet these are the same people who will get up in your face with &quot;war is bad!&quot; or &quot;war is good!&quot; sentiments.
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">
<br />
Being to the far left or right in thinking takes away the grey but makes everything black and white and removes the middle ground, so there is nowhere you can meet inbetween. 
<br />
</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
I'm not really sure if I agree with this, though. It depends on how you define &quot;far right&quot; or &quot;far left.&quot; Most Libertarians, for example, are pretty far right-wing, but they agree with the Green party (who's far left-wing) on marijuana decriminalization. To this day there are people who can't agree whether the Nazis were left-wing or right-wing, mostly because the phrases &quot;left-wing&quot; and &quot;right-wing&quot; are poorly defined.
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">If only the politicians would get a clue and move away from the far ends and back towards the middle.</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
Most &quot;far right&quot; and &quot;far left&quot; folks think that politicians are TOO moderate.
<br />

<br />
The folks on the right who think that all abortion should be banned and that gays shouldn't get coverage under discrimination laws because homosexuality is a &quot;choice&quot; are frothing at the mouth right now. Shift a little away from the religious right into the libertarian right and you have people who believe that all income tax is bad and that corporations should be allowed to do pretty much whatever they want, even if it involves polluting the environment or manufacturing goods that directly threaten people's health.
<br />

<br />
On the left side of that, there are people who believe that all drugs should be legalized, even drugs like cocaine and heroin, that all firearms should be banned and confiscated immediately, or that private medical insurance companies should be dismantled and replaced with a socialized single-payer system funded entirely by income taxes from the rich.
<br />

<br />
Compared to folks at either of these extremes, your average politician is pretty moderate.
<br />

<br />
If anything, the most powerful rhetorical weapon pundits have right now is to paint the opposition as extremist. The entire Nixon-McGovern election came down to Nixon successfully pinning a hippie-loving socialist image on McGovern, and the extremist image has been the tail to pin on the donkey (or elephant) ever since. Right now, Bush and Kerry are trying to do the same to each other.  Both parties are so afraid of moving out of the center that we've ended up with watered-down suit-and-tie Democrats and too-afraid-to-say-anything-of-substance compassionate conservative Republicans.
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">
<br />
Prove my view is wrong, and I mean PROVE, not just beat me over the head with dogma and such, and I will consider changing my view. There are some views I will not change. But those are another discussion all together.
<br />
</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
I'm the same way. I think the biggest problem right now is the oversimplification of issues on <i>both</i> sides.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
