			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Conservatism and Liberalism...<a name="43970"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jun 3 04 2:05 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">
<br />
Call me a roadkill. I am a conservative. The Patriot Act was a necessity following the attack on 9-11.
<br />
</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
This is debatable, but I'm not going to get into that. I just wanted to point out that Bill Clinton tried to push through an anti-terrorism bill in 1996 that had similar wiretapping provisions (although not as broad &amp; far-reaching) as the Patriot Act. (For example, it allowed law enforcement to perform wiretaps on suspected terrorists with a judge's permission without going through the process of getting a warrant. This differs from the Patriot Act, which doesn't even require that they get a judge's permission or even tell anybody what they're doing.) It also contained laws expanding the ability of law enforcement to search records of chemical suppliers and car rental companies for suspicious activity (again, without a warrant but with a judge's informal permission). It basically expanded the laws covering investigation of suspected foreign spies to include suspected terrorists both domestic and foreign. This was in response to the OKC bombing.
<br />

<br />
At the time, the Senate majority leader Trent Lott denounced the bill as being overly invasive of privacy, of being fear-mongering and exploitating the OKC tragedy, which he considered a one-time fluke event. Trent Lott is on record for saying that terrorism is a non-threat and that there's little reason to be scared of terrorist attacks on American soil. Thanks to the Republican majority, Congress eventually passed a neutered version of the bill, which the White House condemned as too watered down.
<br />

<br />
I didn't necessarily support the bill then, so I'm guilty, too. I just think it's interesting how times change.
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">
<br />
Most of the provisions of the act will expire in 2005.
<br />
</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
&quot;Most&quot; would imply a majority. Actually, only about 10% of the provisions of the act sunset in 2005. Now, some of those are highly controversial (such as the provision that allows law enforcement to perform wiretaps without any judicial oversight). However, some of the other provisions do not sunset in 2005 - such as the one that gives law enforcement the right to to do blanket searches of any private business's records, including hotels, car rentals, flight schools, airlines, or just about anything else you can imagine; without telling the business why, without telling them who or what they're looking for, and without clearing the search through a judge or any higher authority. 
<br />

<br />
I don't have a problem with what the Patriot Act allows law enforcement to do - I have a problem with the lack of accountability and oversight. Law enforcement needs to be able to do their job, but there's a reason we have checks and balances like warrants, and I don't think that a law enforcement officer should be able to strongarm any private records they want and not have to justify themselves to anybody.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
