				<td colspan="2"><span>Well, IMO, the drinking age should be lower than the driving age.
<br />
As it is, young people get to have their first experiences drinking and getting ****-faced AFTER they already have their driver's licenses and their first cars. In my opinion, that's backwards.
<br />

<br />
As for state's rights, I wholeheartedly agree. Mostly for selfish reasons. I live in San Francisco. (Amusingly enough, I work close enough to Sony Computer Entertainment that I could probably spit on it from my window if I wanted.) I chose to live in San Francisco partly because it is so liberal. I'm really proud of my city for issuing gay marriage licenses, and I think that a nationwide Constitutional ban on gay marriages is a violation of state's rights.
<br />

<br />
Same with marijuana legalization. The state of California allows sick people to possess small amounts of marijuana. However, the DEA doesn't recognize California's law as being valid and up until a couple of years ago was actively cracking down on patient co-ops. You don't want pot in your state? Fine... ask the DEA for help in keeping it out. I don't think that the feds should encroach on my state.
<br />

<br />
(BTW, it's a myth that if a person gets married in one state that their marriage has to be recognized in every state. There's federal provisions that give any state or local government an out if any given marriage would violate the 'customs' or 'ethics' of that state or locality. This was exercised frequently until 1967 by southern states and cities who refused to acknowledge the validity of interracial marriages.)
<br />

<br />
BTW, I'm neither a pot smoker (I personally hate the stuff) nor am I gay. Just felt the need to point that out.</span></td>
